insert into public.concepts
  (id, term, aliases, said, alias_list, status, one_liner, analogy, example, related, deeper, lens_pm, lens_eng, domain, priority, tags)
values
  ('mixedprecision', 'Mixed precision', 'Mixed-Precision Training', '', ARRAY['mixed precision','mixed-precision training','fp16 training','bf16 training']::text[], 'Core', 'Do most of the training math in low-precision numbers to go faster and use less memory, keeping full precision only where it matters.', 'Rounding to the nearest cent while you shop, but keeping the exact figures for the final tax return.', 'A team switches a training run to bf16 and suddenly the same GPUs fit a bigger batch and finish an epoch in half the time.', '[{"text":"Pairs with this to fit bigger models in memory.","id":"checkpointing"},{"text":"The numbers being rounded are the model weights.","id":"weights"}]'::jsonb, 'Weights and activations are stored and multiplied in 16-bit floats (fp16 or bf16) instead of 32-bit, which roughly halves memory and speeds up the matrix math on modern accelerators. The catch is numerical stability — tiny gradients can underflow to zero — so a full-precision master copy of the weights and loss scaling are kept to stop the training from quietly diverging.', 'It is most of why training the same model got cheaper and faster over the last few years, without changing the recipe.', 'Store/compute in fp16 or bf16 with an fp32 master weight copy and dynamic loss scaling to avoid gradient underflow.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('checkpointing', 'Checkpointing', 'Gradient / Activation Checkpointing', '', ARRAY['checkpointing','gradient checkpointing','activation checkpointing']::text[], 'Core', 'Save memory during training by throwing away intermediate results and recomputing them later, trading extra compute for a smaller footprint.', 'Not keeping every rough draft on your desk — you rewrite a page when you need it instead of storing all of them.', 'A model that would not fit on a single GPU suddenly trains fine once activation checkpointing is turned on, at the cost of a slightly slower step.', '[{"text":"Often used together to squeeze a model onto the hardware.","id":"mixedprecision"},{"text":"A memory-saving trick during the training loop.","id":"training"}]'::jsonb, 'A normal backward pass needs the activations from the forward pass held in memory. Checkpointing keeps only a few of them and recomputes the rest on demand during backprop. You pay for it with a second partial forward pass, but peak memory drops sharply — often the difference between a run that fits and one that OOMs.', 'One of the levers that lets a bigger model train on the hardware you already have.', 'Discard intermediate activations and recompute them in the backward pass to cut peak memory at the cost of ~30% more compute.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('earlystopping', 'Early stopping', 'Early Stopping', '', ARRAY['early stopping','early-stopping']::text[], 'Core', 'Stop training the moment the model stops getting better on held-out data, before it starts memorizing.', 'Taking the cake out when the toothpick comes clean, not leaving it in until the edges burn.', 'A run keeps improving on the training data but its validation loss ticks up at epoch 12 — early stopping halts there and keeps the epoch-11 weights.', '[{"text":"The signal it watches to decide when to quit.","id":"validationset"},{"text":"The thing it is trying to prevent.","id":"overfitting"}]'::jsonb, 'You watch a validation metric each epoch and stop when it has not improved for a set number of rounds (the patience), keeping the best checkpoint seen. It is a cheap, effective guard against overfitting because the point where validation stops improving is roughly where the model shifts from learning patterns to memorizing noise.', 'A simple way to avoid wasting compute and shipping an over-trained model that looks great on paper and worse in the wild.', 'Monitor a validation metric with a patience counter; restore the best checkpoint when it plateaus or regresses.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('validationset', 'Validation set', 'Validation Set / Dev Set', '', ARRAY['validation set','dev set','development set','val set']::text[], 'Core', 'A slice of data the model never trains on, used to tune choices and check progress honestly.', 'The practice exam you grade yourself on — not the real test, but a fair read on whether you are ready.', 'The team compares two learning rates by which one scores better on the validation set, then locks that choice in.', '[{"text":"The data the model actually learns from.","id":"trainingset"},{"text":"The untouched final exam.","id":"testset"},{"text":"Uses this signal to know when to stop.","id":"earlystopping"}]'::jsonb, 'Data is split into training, validation, and test. The validation set guides decisions during development — when to stop, which hyperparameters to pick — without touching the final test set. Because you make choices based on it, the model indirectly adapts to it, which is why the untouched test set still matters for the honest final number.', 'It is how you tell real progress from wishful thinking while a model is still being built.', 'A held-out split used for hyperparameter selection and early stopping, kept separate from the final test set.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('trainingset', 'Training set', 'Training Set / Train Split', '', ARRAY['training set','train split','training data split']::text[], 'Core', 'The data the model actually learns from — the examples it sees over and over.', 'The textbook chapters you study from, as opposed to the exam that tests you on them.', 'A sentiment model is fit on 80,000 labeled reviews in the training set, leaving the rest for validation and test.', '[{"text":"The honest check the model never learns from.","id":"validationset"},{"text":"The final untouched exam.","id":"testset"},{"text":"The huge unlabeled version for base models.","id":"pretrainingcorpus"}]'::jsonb, 'This is the largest split, the material the optimizer minimizes loss over. Everything the model knows traces back to it, which is why its size, quality, and balance matter more than almost any other choice. Anything that leaks from validation or test into here quietly inflates your scores.', 'The quality ceiling of your model is mostly set here — garbage in, garbage out.', 'The split gradients are computed over; guard it against contamination from val/test data.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('testset', 'Test set', 'Test Set / Holdout Test', '', ARRAY['test set','test split','held-out test set']::text[], 'Core', 'The data you touch exactly once, at the very end, to get an honest read on how the model actually does.', 'The sealed final exam — you only open it when you are truly done studying.', 'After weeks of tuning on validation, the team runs the model on the test set a single time and reports that number.', '[{"text":"The dev-time signal you tune against instead.","id":"validationset"},{"text":"What ruins a test set silently.","id":"datacontamination"}]'::jsonb, 'The test set must stay untouched during development, because every peek lets you unconsciously tune toward it and inflate the result. Its whole value is that the model has never adapted to it, so the score generalizes. The moment test data leaks into training — contamination — that guarantee is gone.', 'The one number you can actually trust when deciding whether to ship.', 'A one-shot held-out evaluation split; any reuse or leakage compromises its estimate of generalization.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('holdout', 'Holdout', 'Holdout Set', '', ARRAY['holdout','holdout set','held-out data']::text[], 'Core', 'Any chunk of data you deliberately set aside and keep the model from seeing, so you can test it fairly.', 'Hiding a few puzzle pieces so you can check later whether someone actually solved it or just memorized the picture.', 'Before training, the team carves off 10% of records as a holdout and does not look at it again until the end.', '[{"text":"A holdout used during development.","id":"validationset"},{"text":"Rotates the holdout to use all the data.","id":"crossvalidation"}]'::jsonb, 'Holdout is the general idea behind validation and test splits: withhold data so evaluation reflects performance on examples the model never learned. Simple holdout uses one fixed slice; when data is scarce, cross-validation rotates the holdout across the whole set to use every example both ways.', 'The basic discipline that keeps a demo honest — no holdout, no trustworthy number.', 'Data withheld from training for unbiased evaluation; the fixed-split alternative to cross-validation.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('crossvalidation', 'Cross-validation', 'K-Fold Cross-Validation', '', ARRAY['cross-validation','cross validation','k-fold','k-fold cross-validation']::text[], 'Core', 'Rotate which slice of data is held out so every example gets to be both study material and test, then average the scores.', 'Five friends take turns being the quiz-master while the others answer, so everyone gets tested and no single split decides it.', 'With only 2,000 samples, a team runs 5-fold cross-validation and reports the average accuracy across the five folds.', '[{"text":"The single-split version it generalizes.","id":"holdout"},{"text":"A per-run holdout used during tuning.","id":"validationset"}]'::jsonb, 'Split the data into k folds; train on k−1 and evaluate on the one left out, cycling through so each fold is the holdout once. Averaging the k scores gives a more stable estimate than a single split, which matters most when data is limited. The cost is training k times, so it is common in classic ML and rare for giant models.', 'Buys you a trustworthy number when you do not have enough data to spare a big test set.', 'Partition into k folds, train/evaluate k times rotating the held-out fold, and average the metric.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('hyperparameter', 'Hyperparameter', 'Hyperparameter', '', ARRAY['hyperparameter','hyper-parameter','hyperparameters']::text[], 'Core', 'A setting you choose before training that shapes how learning happens, as opposed to a weight the model learns on its own.', 'The oven temperature and bake time — you set them; the cake does not decide them for you.', 'Learning rate, batch size, and number of layers are all hyperparameters picked before the run starts.', '[{"text":"The process of searching over these settings.","id":"hyperparametertuning"},{"text":"The single most sensitive one.","id":"learningrate"},{"text":"What the model learns instead.","id":"parameters"}]'::jsonb, 'Parameters (weights) are learned by gradient descent; hyperparameters are the dials outside that loop — learning rate, batch size, dropout, architecture size. They are not differentiable with respect to the loss, so you cannot train them directly; you search over them by trying values and comparing on validation data.', 'The knobs that decide whether a training run succeeds, wastes money, or quietly underperforms.', 'Configuration set outside the optimization loop; tuned via search rather than gradients.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('hyperparametertuning', 'Hyperparameter tuning', 'Hyperparameter Optimization', '', ARRAY['hyperparameter tuning','hyperparameter optimization','hpo','hyperparameter search']::text[], 'Core', 'The trial-and-error hunt for the training settings that make a model work best.', 'Dialing in a new espresso machine — adjust grind, dose, and time, taste, repeat until it is right.', 'A team sweeps learning rates from 1e-5 to 1e-3 and batch sizes of 16, 32, 64, then keeps the combo with the best validation loss.', '[{"text":"The settings being searched over.","id":"hyperparameter"},{"text":"The brute-force version of the search.","id":"gridsearch"}]'::jsonb, 'Because hyperparameters are not learned by gradients, you search: try configurations, measure each on validation data, keep the winner. Strategies range from brute-force grid search to random search to smarter Bayesian methods that spend trials where they seem promising. The cost is that each trial is a full training run, so it gets expensive fast at scale.', 'Often the difference between a mediocre and a strong model — and a real line item in the compute budget.', 'Search over hyperparameters (grid, random, or Bayesian) using validation performance as the objective.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('gridsearch', 'Grid search', 'Grid Search', '', ARRAY['grid search','grid-search']::text[], 'Fading', 'Try every combination of a fixed set of settings, exhaustively, and pick the best.', 'Testing every pairing on a menu — each starter with each main — to find the one you like most.', 'A team lists 3 learning rates and 3 batch sizes and runs all 9 combinations to see which wins.', '[{"text":"The broader activity it is one method for.","id":"hyperparametertuning"}]'::jsonb, 'Grid search enumerates the full Cartesian product of candidate values. It is simple and reproducible but scales terribly — adding one more hyperparameter multiplies the runs — and it wastes effort on dimensions that barely matter. Random search often finds comparable settings for less compute, which is why grid search is fading for anything beyond a couple of knobs.', 'Thorough but expensive; fine for a tiny search, wasteful for a big one.', 'Exhaustive evaluation over the Cartesian product of hyperparameter values; cost grows exponentially with dimensions.', 'Training', 30, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('scalinglaws', 'Scaling laws', 'Neural Scaling Laws', '', ARRAY['scaling laws','scaling law','neural scaling laws']::text[], 'Core', 'The predictable way model quality improves as you add more data, parameters, and compute — smooth enough to plan around.', 'Knowing that doubling the ingredients and oven time reliably yields a bigger, better-baked loaf — the recipe scales.', 'Before committing to a huge run, a lab uses scaling-law curves fit on small models to predict the loss the big one will hit.', '[{"text":"Uses scaling laws to balance model and data size.","id":"chinchillascaling"},{"text":"The compute-efficient point on the curve.","id":"computeoptimal"},{"text":"Capabilities scaling laws do not directly predict.","id":"emergence"}]'::jsonb, 'Empirically, test loss falls as a power law in model size, dataset size, and compute — straight lines on a log-log plot across many orders of magnitude. This let labs forecast returns and justify spending on ever-larger runs. The laws describe loss, not capability, and they do not promise where useful behaviors emerge, so they guide budgets more than they guarantee outcomes.', 'The reason "just make it bigger" became a credible strategy — the payoff was forecastable.', 'Power-law relationships between test loss and compute/params/data used to extrapolate and allocate budgets.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('computeoptimal', 'Compute-optimal', 'Compute-Optimal Training', '', ARRAY['compute-optimal','compute optimal','compute-optimal training']::text[], 'Rising', 'Splitting a fixed compute budget between model size and data so you get the lowest loss for the money.', 'With a set grocery budget, choosing the mix of ingredients that makes the best meal — not just the biggest one.', 'Given a fixed number of GPU-hours, a team picks a smaller model trained on more tokens because the math says it lands lower loss than a bigger, under-fed one.', '[{"text":"The result that defined this sweet spot.","id":"chinchillascaling"},{"text":"The curves this optimizes along.","id":"scalinglaws"},{"text":"The ratio at the heart of the trade-off.","id":"tokensperparameter"}]'::jsonb, 'For a fixed compute budget, there is a sweet spot in how you trade parameters against training tokens. The Chinchilla work showed many large models were over-parameterized and under-trained — too big for the data they saw. Compute-optimal means sitting at that frontier, though it optimizes training cost, not inference cost, so deployment concerns can push you smaller still.', 'It reframed "bigger is better" into "right-sized for the data" — and made many models cheaper to serve.', 'Allocate a fixed FLOPs budget between N (params) and D (tokens) to minimize loss, per Chinchilla-style scaling.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('chinchillascaling', 'Chinchilla scaling', 'Chinchilla-Optimal Scaling', '', ARRAY['chinchilla scaling','chinchilla-optimal','chinchilla scaling laws']::text[], 'Rising', 'The finding that for a given compute budget, models should be smaller and trained on far more data than people assumed.', 'Realizing a smaller pot on the stove longer cooks better than a giant pot rushed — more time with the heat beats sheer size.', 'Chinchilla matched a much larger model using fewer parameters but roughly four times the training tokens, at the same compute.', '[{"text":"The general principle it is the flagship result of.","id":"computeoptimal"},{"text":"The ratio it pinned down.","id":"tokensperparameter"},{"text":"The curves it sits on.","id":"scalinglaws"}]'::jsonb, 'DeepMind''s 2022 study showed the compute-optimal ratio is roughly 20 training tokens per parameter — meaning earlier giant models were under-trained. It shifted the field toward smaller, data-hungrier models, which also happen to be cheaper to run. In practice teams now often train well past the Chinchilla point because inference savings justify over-training a smaller model.', 'It quietly rewrote sizing decisions industry-wide and made strong small models the norm.', 'Empirical result: ~20 tokens/param is compute-optimal; smaller models on more data beat larger under-trained ones.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('datamixture', 'Data mixture', 'Training Data Mixture', '', ARRAY['data mixture','data mix','training data mixture']::text[], 'Rising', 'The recipe of how much of each kind of data — web, code, books, math — goes into training, and in what proportion.', 'A coffee blend: the ratio of beans changes the whole cup, even with the same total amount.', 'A team bumps the share of code and math in the mixture and the model gets noticeably better at reasoning, at a slight cost to prose.', '[{"text":"The full pool the mixture is drawn from.","id":"pretrainingcorpus"},{"text":"How sources are cleaned before mixing.","id":"datacuration"}]'::jsonb, 'Pretraining data comes from many sources with very different value, and their proportions strongly shape the final model. Teams up-weight high-quality or scarce domains, sometimes repeat certain sources, and tune the blend by training small proxy models. The mixture is one of the most guarded and impactful recipes in a lab, because it trades strengths off against each other.', 'A hidden dial that decides what your model is naturally good and bad at.', 'The sampling proportions across data sources during pretraining; tuned via proxy runs and domain weighting.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('tokensperparameter', 'Tokens per parameter', 'Token-to-Parameter Ratio', '', ARRAY['tokens per parameter','token-to-parameter ratio','tokens-per-parameter']::text[], 'Rising', 'How many training tokens each model parameter gets to learn from — a rough gauge of whether a model is well-fed or starved.', 'Students per teacher: too many and each gets too little attention; the ratio tells you if the class is well-served.', 'A 7B model trained on 2 trillion tokens sees about 285 tokens per parameter — far past the Chinchilla point of 20, on purpose.', '[{"text":"The study that fixed the optimal value near 20.","id":"chinchillascaling"},{"text":"The trade-off this ratio expresses.","id":"computeoptimal"}]'::jsonb, 'Divide training tokens by parameter count. Chinchilla put the compute-optimal ratio near 20, but modern small models are trained to hundreds of tokens per parameter because over-training a small model buys cheaper inference. A low ratio suggests an under-trained, over-sized model; a very high one means you are spending extra training compute to save at serving time.', 'A quick sniff test for whether a model is right-sized for its data budget.', 'Training tokens ÷ parameters; ~20 is compute-optimal, higher trades train cost for inference savings.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('emergence', 'Emergence', 'Emergent Behavior', '', ARRAY['emergence','emergent behavior','emergent behaviour']::text[], 'Rising', 'When a capability appears fairly suddenly at a certain scale, seeming absent in smaller models and present in bigger ones.', 'Water that just sits there as you heat it — until it hits a boil and abruptly changes state.', 'Small models score near-random on multi-step arithmetic, then past a size threshold they start getting it right, seemingly out of nowhere.', '[{"text":"Predicts loss but not when abilities appear.","id":"scalinglaws"},{"text":"The broader notion of scale-unlocked skills.","id":"emergentability"}]'::jsonb, 'As models scale, some skills improve smoothly while others look like sharp jumps. Debate continues over how "real" the sharpness is — some apparent leaps flatten out under smoother metrics, suggesting the jump is partly an artifact of harsh pass/fail scoring. Either way, it complicates planning: scaling laws predict loss well but not exactly when a given ability shows up.', 'Why you cannot always promise a feature at a target size — some abilities only show up when they show up.', 'Capabilities that appear abruptly with scale; partly metric-dependent and not directly forecast by loss curves.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('rewardhacking', 'Reward hacking', 'Reward Hacking / Specification Gaming', '', ARRAY['reward hacking','specification gaming','reward gaming']::text[], 'Rising', 'When a model learns to game the score instead of doing the thing the score was supposed to measure.', 'A student who memorizes the answer key instead of learning the subject — perfect grade, no understanding.', 'A model rewarded for helpful-sounding answers learns to be verbose and flattering, scoring high while actually being less useful.', '[{"text":"The proxy being exploited.","id":"rewardmodel"},{"text":"Adjusting rewards, which can invite this.","id":"rewardshaping"},{"text":"A common hacked behavior.","id":"rewardsignal"}]'::jsonb, 'Any reward is a proxy for what you really want, and optimizers exploit the gap. During RL fine-tuning a model may find shortcuts — sycophancy, padding, exploiting quirks of the reward model — that boost the number without improving the true goal. It is why reward models need to be robust, why KL penalties keep the policy from drifting too far, and why human spot-checks stay in the loop.', 'A core reason a model can ace its metrics and still feel worse to real users.', 'The policy exploits flaws in the reward proxy; mitigated by robust reward models, KL constraints, and held-out human eval.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('rewardshaping', 'Reward shaping', 'Reward Shaping', '', ARRAY['reward shaping','shaped reward']::text[], 'Core', 'Adding extra hints to the reward so the model gets feedback along the way, not just at the very end.', 'Giving a kid "warmer, warmer, colder" clues while they search, instead of only saying "found it" at the end.', 'Rather than rewarding only a fully correct final answer, a trainer gives partial credit for each valid reasoning step to guide learning.', '[{"text":"What careless shaping can cause.","id":"rewardhacking"},{"text":"The base signal being shaped.","id":"rewardsignal"}]'::jsonb, 'Sparse rewards are hard to learn from because most actions get zero signal. Shaping adds intermediate rewards to point the model toward good behavior sooner. The danger is that a poorly shaped reward changes what is optimal and invites reward hacking — the model chases the hints rather than the real goal — so shaping has to be designed carefully to preserve the true objective.', 'Speeds up learning on hard tasks, but a sloppy shaping function can teach the wrong lesson.', 'Augment sparse rewards with intermediate signals; keep them potential-based to avoid altering the optimal policy.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('policygradient', 'Policy gradient', 'Policy Gradient Methods', '', ARRAY['policy gradient','policy gradients','policy gradient methods']::text[], 'Core', 'A way to train by nudging the model to make rewarded actions more likely and penalized ones less likely.', 'Training a dog with treats — reward the behaviors you want and they happen more; ignore the ones you do not.', 'During RLHF, a policy-gradient update pushes up the probability of responses the reward model liked and pushes down the ones it disliked.', '[{"text":"The stabilized workhorse version.","id":"ppo"},{"text":"The setting it is used in.","id":"reinforcementlearning"}]'::jsonb, 'Policy-gradient methods directly optimize the model (the policy) by estimating how changing an action''s probability affects expected reward, then stepping in that direction. They are noisy because reward is sparse and estimates are high-variance, which is why practical algorithms like PPO add tricks — clipping, baselines, KL penalties — to keep updates stable.', 'The learning machinery underneath reinforcement-learning fine-tuning like RLHF.', 'Optimize expected reward by ascending the gradient of log-prob weighted by advantage; high variance, stabilized by PPO-style methods.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('ppo', 'PPO', 'Proximal Policy Optimization', '“P-P-O”', ARRAY['ppo','proximal policy optimization']::text[], 'Core', 'The reinforcement-learning algorithm that powered classic RLHF, designed to improve the model without letting each update lurch too far.', 'Adjusting a recipe one careful pinch at a time — never dumping in a whole cup and ruining the batch.', 'A lab fine-tunes a chat model with PPO against a reward model, keeping a KL leash so it stays close to the original model.', '[{"text":"The family of methods it belongs to.","id":"policygradient"},{"text":"The training regime it implements.","id":"rlhf"},{"text":"The leash that keeps it close to the base model.","id":"kldivergence"},{"text":"The simpler alternative that skips the RL loop.","id":"dpo"}]'::jsonb, 'PPO is a policy-gradient method that caps how much the policy can change per step, using a clipped objective and a KL penalty against a reference model. That restraint is what makes RL on language models stable enough to work. It is effective but fiddly — many moving parts and hyperparameters — which is part of why simpler alternatives like DPO gained ground.', 'The engine behind the first wave of aligned chat models; powerful but operationally heavy.', 'Clipped-objective policy gradient with a KL penalty to a reference policy, stabilizing RLHF updates.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('kldivergence', 'KL divergence', 'Kullback–Leibler Divergence', '“K-L divergence”', ARRAY['kl divergence','kullback-leibler divergence','kl penalty']::text[], 'Core', 'A measure of how far one probability distribution has drifted from another — used as a leash to keep a fine-tuned model near its original.', 'A tether on a climber: it lets them move around but yanks back if they stray too far from base camp.', 'In RLHF, a KL penalty rises as the tuned model''s outputs diverge from the base model, discouraging it from going off the rails to chase reward.', '[{"text":"Uses it as a constraint each step.","id":"ppo"},{"text":"A related information-theoretic loss.","id":"crossentropy"}]'::jsonb, 'KL divergence quantifies the difference between two distributions and is not symmetric — the direction matters. In RL fine-tuning it appears as a penalty term measuring how far the current policy has moved from the reference model; this keeps the model from exploiting the reward at the cost of coherence or safety. It also shows up broadly in training objectives like variational methods.', 'The safety tether that stops reward-chasing from turning a good model into a weird one.', 'A non-symmetric distance between distributions; used as a regularizing penalty against a reference policy in RLHF.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('rewardsignal', 'Reward signal', 'Reward Signal', '', ARRAY['reward signal','reward']::text[], 'Core', 'The number that tells a reinforcement-learning model how good an action or output was — the thing it tries to maximize.', 'The score in a video game: it is the only feedback telling you whether that last move helped or hurt.', 'A reward model scores each candidate response, and that score is the reward signal the policy learns to push upward.', '[{"text":"Usually produces this signal.","id":"rewardmodel"},{"text":"Adding intermediate versions of it.","id":"rewardshaping"},{"text":"What a bad signal invites.","id":"rewardhacking"}]'::jsonb, 'In RL the model does not get labeled right answers; it gets a scalar reward and figures out which behaviors produce more of it. The signal can be sparse (only at the end) or shaped (along the way), and it is always a proxy for the true goal — which is why a flawed reward signal leads straight to reward hacking. Its quality bounds how good the trained model can get.', 'Whatever you actually reward is what you actually get — so defining it well is half the battle.', 'The scalar feedback the policy optimizes; sparse or shaped, and always a proxy prone to exploitation.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('humanfeedback', 'Human feedback', 'Human Feedback', '', ARRAY['human feedback','human preferences','human ratings']::text[], 'Core', 'People judging model outputs — usually by comparing them — to teach the model what "good" looks like.', 'A taste-test panel picking which of two dishes they prefer, over and over, until the chef learns the room.', 'Annotators are shown two model replies and click the better one; thousands of these comparisons train the reward model.', '[{"text":"The framework it feeds.","id":"rlhf"},{"text":"Keeping people in the loop generally.","id":"hitl"},{"text":"The dataset it produces.","id":"preferencedata"}]'::jsonb, 'Human feedback is how fuzzy human values — helpful, honest, harmless — get injected into training. It usually takes the form of pairwise preferences rather than absolute scores, since people are more consistent at comparing than rating. Those preferences train a reward model or feed directly into methods like DPO. Its limits are human ones: bias, fatigue, and disagreement all leak in.', 'The raw material that turns a raw predictor into something people actually want to talk to.', 'Human preference judgments (often pairwise) used to train reward models or drive preference optimization.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('preferenceoptimization', 'Preference optimization', 'Preference Optimization', '', ARRAY['preference optimization','preference-based optimization','preference learning']::text[], 'Rising', 'Training a model directly from "this answer is better than that one" comparisons to make preferred outputs more likely.', 'Teaching taste by always pointing at the better of two plates, until the cook internalizes what you like.', 'Instead of running full RL, a team applies DPO on a dataset of chosen-vs-rejected pairs and the model shifts toward the chosen style.', '[{"text":"The method that popularized skipping RL.","id":"dpo"},{"text":"The data it consumes.","id":"preferencedata"},{"text":"The RL-based approach it competes with.","id":"rlhf"}]'::jsonb, 'This family reframes alignment as learning from pairwise preferences. Classic RLHF does it indirectly — train a reward model, then optimize with RL. Newer methods like DPO skip the separate reward model and the RL loop, deriving an objective that directly raises the probability of preferred responses over dispreferred ones. Simpler and more stable, though sometimes less flexible than full RL.', 'The trend that made preference-based training cheaper and more reliable to run.', 'Optimize a policy on chosen/rejected pairs; DPO-style objectives bypass an explicit reward model and RL loop.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('rejectionsampling', 'Rejection sampling', 'Rejection Sampling', '', ARRAY['rejection sampling','rejection-sampling']::text[], 'Rising', 'Generate several candidate answers, keep only the good ones, and train on those.', 'Baking a dozen cookies, keeping the best few, and photographing only those for the recipe card.', 'A model produces eight solutions per math problem; a checker keeps the correct ones, and those become new training data.', '[{"text":"The inference-time cousin that keeps just one.","id":"bestofn"},{"text":"The generation step it filters.","id":"sampling"}]'::jsonb, 'Rejection sampling filters a model''s own generations by some quality bar — a verifier, a reward model, or an exact-answer check — and fine-tunes on the survivors. It is a simple, stable way to bootstrap a model on its better outputs, closely related to best-of-n but used to build a training set rather than to pick a single response at inference time.', 'A cheap way to squeeze more quality out of a model using its own best work.', 'Sample n candidates, keep those passing a quality/verifier filter, and fine-tune on the accepted set.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('bestofn', 'Best-of-n', 'Best-of-N Sampling', '', ARRAY['best-of-n','best of n','bon sampling']::text[], 'Rising', 'Generate several answers and return only the one a scorer likes best — better output for more compute.', 'Asking three people to draft the same email and sending only the strongest one.', 'For a tricky query, the system samples five completions, ranks them with a reward model, and shows the top-ranked reply.', '[{"text":"The training-data version of the same idea.","id":"rejectionsampling"},{"text":"The scorer that picks the winner.","id":"rewardmodel"}]'::jsonb, 'Best-of-n trades inference compute for quality: sample n candidates, score them with a reward or verifier, output the winner. It reliably lifts quality but with diminishing returns and n-times the cost. It is closely tied to rejection sampling — same generate-and-filter idea — and its scores can be distilled back into the model so you get the benefit without paying at serve time.', 'A dial to buy better answers with more compute, useful when quality matters more than latency.', 'Sample n outputs, rank with a scorer, return the argmax; quality rises sublinearly with n.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('selfdistillation', 'Self-distillation', 'Self-Distillation', '', ARRAY['self-distillation','self distillation']::text[], 'Rising', 'A model teaching itself by training on its own best outputs, rather than learning from a bigger teacher.', 'Reviewing your own strongest essays and studying them to write even better ones next time.', 'A model generates answers, keeps the ones a verifier approves, and fine-tunes on them — bootstrapping itself upward without a larger model.', '[{"text":"The teacher-student version it is derived from.","id":"distillation"},{"text":"The self-generated data it relies on.","id":"syntheticdata"}]'::jsonb, 'Ordinary distillation transfers knowledge from a large teacher to a smaller student. Self-distillation drops the separate teacher: the model produces outputs, filters them for quality, and trains on the survivors, often over several rounds. It works because generating a good answer can be easier than learning to produce it consistently. Gains taper and can amplify the model''s own biases, so filtering quality is everything.', 'A way to improve a model without access to a bigger one — but it can entrench existing quirks.', 'Train a model on its own filtered generations, iteratively, without a separate teacher network.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('teacherforcing', 'Teacher forcing', 'Teacher Forcing', '', ARRAY['teacher forcing','teacher-forcing']::text[], 'Core', 'During training, feed the model the real previous word instead of its own guess, so mistakes do not snowball.', 'A music teacher who plays the correct next note for a student mid-piece, so one slip does not derail the whole song.', 'While training a language model, each step is conditioned on the true prior tokens from the text, not on what the model itself predicted.', '[{"text":"The generation style it trains.","id":"autoregressive"},{"text":"The objective it is used with.","id":"nexttokenprediction"}]'::jsonb, 'Autoregressive models generate one token from the previous ones. Teacher forcing trains them on the ground-truth prefix rather than their own outputs, which makes training stable and parallelizable. The downside is exposure bias: at inference the model must feed on its own outputs, so early errors can compound — a mismatch between how it was trained and how it actually runs.', 'A training shortcut that speeds learning but partly explains why long generations can drift.', 'Condition each training step on ground-truth prior tokens; efficient but introduces exposure bias at inference.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('labelsmoothing', 'Label smoothing', 'Label Smoothing', '', ARRAY['label smoothing','label-smoothing']::text[], 'Core', 'Tell the model the right answer is "very likely" rather than "100% certain," so it stays humble and generalizes better.', 'A teacher who marks the answer correct but reminds you nothing is ever quite certain, keeping you from overconfidence.', 'Instead of a target of exactly 1.0 for the correct class, training uses 0.9, spreading the remaining 0.1 across the others.', '[{"text":"The loss it modifies.","id":"crossentropy"},{"text":"The problem it helps guard against.","id":"overfitting"},{"text":"The broader family it belongs to.","id":"regularization"}]'::jsonb, 'Standard cross-entropy pushes the model toward assigning all probability to the correct token, which encourages overconfidence and sharp, brittle outputs. Label smoothing softens the target — a little probability mass is spread to the wrong classes — which regularizes the model, improves calibration, and often generalizes better. Too much smoothing, though, blurs genuine distinctions.', 'A small tweak that makes a model''s confidence more trustworthy and less brittle.', 'Replace one-hot targets with a softened distribution; regularizes and improves calibration under cross-entropy.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('datacuration', 'Data curation', 'Data Curation', '', ARRAY['data curation','dataset curation','data curating']::text[], 'Core', 'The careful work of choosing, cleaning, and organizing training data so a model learns from good material.', 'A librarian deciding which books belong on the shelf and which get pulled — the collection is only as good as the choices.', 'Before a pretraining run, a team dedupes documents, strips boilerplate, drops low-quality pages, and balances the sources.', '[{"text":"The filtering step within it.","id":"datafiltering"},{"text":"The proportions it sets.","id":"datamixture"},{"text":"The raw pool it refines.","id":"pretrainingcorpus"}]'::jsonb, 'Curation spans deduplication, quality filtering, removing toxic or private content, balancing domains, and deciding what to include at all. It is unglamorous but decisive — many of the biggest quality jumps between model generations came from better data, not bigger models. The hard part is that "quality" is fuzzy and every filter trades some coverage for cleanliness.', 'Often the highest-leverage, least-visible work behind a model that just feels better.', 'The pipeline of selection, cleaning, dedup, and balancing that determines pretraining data quality.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('datafiltering', 'Data filtering', 'Data Filtering', '', ARRAY['data filtering','data filter','content filtering']::text[], 'Core', 'Automatically dropping unwanted data — junk, duplicates, toxic or unsafe content — before it reaches training.', 'A coffee filter: it lets the good stuff through and holds back the grounds.', 'A classifier flags spam, gibberish, and near-duplicate pages, and those documents never make it into the training set.', '[{"text":"The narrower quality-focused version.","id":"qualityfiltering"},{"text":"The broader process it is part of.","id":"datacuration"},{"text":"A specific filtering step.","id":"deduplication"}]'::jsonb, 'Filtering applies rules and learned classifiers to remove data you do not want the model to learn from: boilerplate, machine-translated junk, adult or harmful content, personal information, and duplicates. It is a core piece of curation. The tension is precision versus recall — aggressive filters cut noise but also throw away useful examples and can bake in the filter''s own biases.', 'Decides what your model never sees — and therefore some of what it will never do.', 'Rule- and classifier-based removal of low-quality, unsafe, or duplicate documents from the corpus.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('qualityfiltering', 'Quality filtering', 'Quality Filtering', '', ARRAY['quality filtering','quality filter','quality classifier']::text[], 'Rising', 'Keeping only the higher-quality documents by scoring each one and dropping the bottom of the barrel.', 'Grading apples and shipping only the ones above a certain bar, composting the bruised ones.', 'A classifier trained to recognize well-written pages scores the web crawl, and only documents above a threshold are kept.', '[{"text":"The broader filtering step it lives in.","id":"datafiltering"},{"text":"The overall data process.","id":"datacuration"}]'::jsonb, 'A specific slice of filtering focused on "is this good writing/useful content" rather than "is this unsafe." Often a small model is trained to imitate a known-good reference (say, curated encyclopedic text) and used to score the rest of the corpus. It reliably boosts model quality, but the reference defines "quality," so the choice quietly shapes what the model treats as normal or authoritative.', 'A big lever on final model quality — and on whose writing style gets treated as the standard.', 'Score documents with a learned quality classifier against a reference distribution and threshold the corpus.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('datapipeline', 'Data pipeline', 'Data Pipeline', '', ARRAY['data pipeline','data-processing pipeline','preprocessing pipeline']::text[], 'Core', 'The assembly line that turns raw data into clean, tokenized, training-ready batches.', 'A factory line: raw ingredients go in one end, cleaned and packaged product comes out the other.', 'Raw web dumps flow through the pipeline — deduped, filtered, tokenized, shuffled, and sharded — before the trainer ever sees a batch.', '[{"text":"The judgment-heavy part of the pipeline.","id":"datacuration"},{"text":"A step near the end of it.","id":"tokenization"}]'::jsonb, 'The pipeline is the engineered sequence of steps between raw sources and the optimizer: ingestion, cleaning, filtering, deduplication, tokenization, shuffling, and sharding into an efficient on-disk format. At scale it must be fast and reproducible, because reprocessing petabytes is expensive. Bugs here — a bad shuffle, a leaky filter — silently corrupt training in ways that are hard to trace later.', 'Invisible plumbing whose reliability quietly determines whether a training run is trustworthy.', 'The reproducible ETL from raw sources to tokenized, shuffled, sharded training batches.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('pretrainingcorpus', 'Pretraining corpus', 'Pretraining Corpus', '', ARRAY['pretraining corpus','pretraining data','training corpus']::text[], 'Core', 'The giant pile of mostly-web text (and code, and more) a base model reads to learn language in the first place.', 'The entire library a student reads growing up — it shapes everything they later know or assume.', 'A base model''s pretraining corpus might be trillions of tokens drawn from web crawls, books, code, and reference sites.', '[{"text":"The stage that consumes it.","id":"pretraining"},{"text":"A major source within it.","id":"webcrawl"},{"text":"The proportions across sources.","id":"datamixture"}]'::jsonb, 'Pretraining is where the model gets its raw knowledge and language ability, and the corpus is its whole world at that stage. Its scale is measured in trillions of tokens, its composition (the data mixture) shapes strengths and biases, and whatever is absent from it the model simply will not know. Later fine-tuning polishes behavior but rarely adds fundamentally new knowledge the corpus lacked.', 'The source of a model''s baseline knowledge — and of the blind spots you inherit.', 'The large, mostly self-supervised text corpus consumed during pretraining; defines the model''s knowledge base.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('webcrawl', 'Web crawl', 'Web Crawl Data', '', ARRAY['web crawl','web-crawled data','crawled web data']::text[], 'Core', 'Text scraped in bulk from across the public internet — the messy backbone of most pretraining data.', 'Emptying the whole internet into a bin and then sorting it — most of the volume, most of the mess.', 'A team starts from a raw web crawl of billions of pages, then filters it down to the fraction worth training on.', '[{"text":"The best-known public crawl.","id":"commoncrawl"},{"text":"The pool it feeds.","id":"pretrainingcorpus"}]'::jsonb, 'Web crawls provide the sheer scale that pretraining needs, but they are enormously noisy — spam, boilerplate, duplicates, machine text, and worse. Their usefulness depends almost entirely on aggressive cleaning and filtering afterward. Common Crawl is the best-known public source; labs also run private crawls. The web''s biases and gaps flow straight into the model unless curation catches them.', 'Cheap scale, but its raw quality is low — the value is in what you do to it after.', 'Bulk-scraped public web text; high-volume, low-signal until filtered and deduplicated.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('commoncrawl', 'Common Crawl', 'Common Crawl', '', ARRAY['common crawl','commoncrawl']::text[], 'Core', 'A free, public archive of web-crawl data that underpins a large share of AI training corpora.', 'A public reservoir everyone draws from — you still have to filter the water before you drink it.', 'Many open datasets start from Common Crawl snapshots, then apply their own cleaning to produce a usable subset.', '[{"text":"The kind of data it provides.","id":"webcrawl"},{"text":"What it ultimately feeds.","id":"pretrainingcorpus"}]'::jsonb, 'Common Crawl is a nonprofit that has crawled the web for years and releases petabyte-scale snapshots for free. It is the raw feedstock behind well-known derived datasets, which apply heavy filtering to it. Because so many models trace back to it, its coverage and gaps — languages, domains, time periods — quietly shape the field. It is raw material, not a ready-to-use dataset.', 'A shared starting point that makes strong base data accessible, but never usable straight out of the box.', 'Public multi-petabyte web-crawl snapshots used as the base feedstock for derived pretraining datasets.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('tokenizertraining', 'Tokenizer training', 'Tokenizer Training', '', ARRAY['tokenizer training','training a tokenizer','tokenizer fitting']::text[], 'Core', 'Building the model''s vocabulary by finding which character chunks are common enough to deserve their own token.', 'Deciding which phrases are common enough to earn a shorthand in your notes, so you write less.', 'A team runs byte-pair encoding over the corpus, merging frequent character pairs until it has a 100k-token vocabulary.', '[{"text":"The result it produces.","id":"vocabulary"},{"text":"The size decision it involves.","id":"vocabularysize"},{"text":"The common algorithm used.","id":"bytepairencoding"}]'::jsonb, 'Before a model trains, its tokenizer is fit on a data sample, usually with byte-pair encoding or a similar algorithm that repeatedly merges the most frequent adjacent units. The result is the fixed vocabulary the model will use forever. It matters because it decides how efficiently text is encoded — a tokenizer fit mostly on English will chop other languages into many more tokens, making them costlier and often worse-served.', 'A one-time choice that quietly sets per-language cost and quality for the model''s whole life.', 'Fit a subword vocabulary (e.g. BPE) on a corpus sample by iterative frequency-based merges; fixed thereafter.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('vocabularysize', 'Vocabulary size', 'Vocabulary Size', '', ARRAY['vocabulary size','vocab size']::text[], 'Core', 'How many distinct tokens the model knows — a trade-off between shorter sequences and a bigger, heavier vocabulary.', 'The number of keys on a keyboard: more keys means fewer keystrokes per word, but a bulkier keyboard.', 'Bumping the vocabulary from 32k to 128k tokens lets the model encode the same text in fewer tokens, especially in other languages.', '[{"text":"The process that sets it.","id":"tokenizertraining"},{"text":"The set of tokens it counts.","id":"vocabulary"}]'::jsonb, 'A larger vocabulary encodes text in fewer tokens — cheaper and faster context-wise — but inflates the embedding and output layers, adding parameters and memory. Too small and everything fragments into many tokens; too large and rare tokens are undertrained and the model gets heavier. Modern models trend toward larger vocabularies partly to serve many languages more fairly.', 'A dial affecting speed, cost, and how well non-English text is handled.', 'The token count in the vocabulary; larger shortens sequences but enlarges embedding/output layers.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('contextextension', 'Context extension', 'Context Window Extension', '', ARRAY['context extension','context window extension','context length extension']::text[], 'Rising', 'Stretching a model to handle much longer inputs than it was originally trained for.', 'Adding leaves to a dining table so it seats far more guests than the original build allowed.', 'A model trained at 8k tokens is extended to 128k so it can read whole books, using adjusted positional encodings and a bit of long-context fine-tuning.', '[{"text":"The limit it raises.","id":"contextlength"},{"text":"The fine-tuning phase it relies on.","id":"longcontexttraining"},{"text":"The mechanism it modifies.","id":"positionalencoding"}]'::jsonb, 'Models learn positional patterns only up to their training length, so naively feeding more tokens breaks them. Extension techniques modify how positions are encoded — for example interpolating rotary embeddings — often followed by fine-tuning on longer sequences. It works, but longer context is not free: attention cost grows and models often use the far reaches of a long window unevenly.', 'How a model gains the ability to handle long documents without retraining from scratch.', 'Adapt positional encodings (e.g. RoPE interpolation) plus long-sequence fine-tuning to extend usable context.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('longcontexttraining', 'Long-context training', 'Long-Context Training', '', ARRAY['long-context training','long context training']::text[], 'Rising', 'Fine-tuning a model on very long sequences so it can actually use a big context window, not just accept one.', 'Practicing with a full-length novel, not just short passages, so you can genuinely follow a long story.', 'After extending a model to 128k tokens, the team trains it on long documents so it learns to track information across the whole span.', '[{"text":"The step that raises the ceiling first.","id":"contextextension"},{"text":"The failure it combats.","id":"lostinthemiddle"},{"text":"The window it makes usable.","id":"contextlength"}]'::jsonb, 'Accepting long inputs and using them well are different things. Long-context training exposes the model to genuinely long sequences during fine-tuning so it learns to attend across distances it never saw in pretraining. It is expensive — attention and memory scale with sequence length — and it directly fights the "lost in the middle" tendency where models under-use the center of a long input.', 'The work that turns a big advertised context window into one that actually performs.', 'Fine-tune on long sequences post-extension so attention learns to use the full window; costly in memory/compute.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('alignmenttax', 'Alignment tax', 'Alignment Tax / Safety Tax', '', ARRAY['alignment tax','safety tax']::text[], 'Rising', 'The capability you sometimes give up when you make a model safer and more aligned.', 'Speed bumps in a parking lot: safer for everyone, but they slow you down a little.', 'After heavy safety fine-tuning, a model refuses a few too many harmless requests and loses a bit of sharpness on hard tasks — that gap is the alignment tax.', '[{"text":"A main contributor to the tax.","id":"refusaltraining"},{"text":"The training that can levy it.","id":"safetyfinetuning"},{"text":"The overall goal it is a cost of.","id":"alignment"}]'::jsonb, 'Aligning a model — refusal training, safety tuning, RLHF toward cautious behavior — can trade away raw capability or usefulness: over-refusal, blander answers, hedging. The "tax" is that cost. Good alignment work aims to shrink it toward zero, and modern methods have narrowed it a lot, but a tension remains between being maximally helpful and reliably safe.', 'The real trade-off behind "why won''t it just answer" — safety and helpfulness pull against each other.', 'The capability/usefulness loss incurred by alignment training; minimized but rarely fully eliminated.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('refusaltraining', 'Refusal training', 'Refusal Training', '', ARRAY['refusal training','refusal tuning','teaching refusals']::text[], 'Rising', 'Teaching a model to decline requests it should not fulfill, and to do it gracefully.', 'Training a bartender to firmly but politely cut someone off — knowing when "no" is the right answer.', 'The model is fine-tuned on examples where the good response to a harmful request is a clear, polite refusal with a brief reason.', '[{"text":"The broader safety phase it is part of.","id":"safetyfinetuning"},{"text":"The cost of over-refusal.","id":"alignmenttax"}]'::jsonb, 'Refusal behavior is taught with curated examples and preference data showing when and how to say no. The craft is calibration: refuse genuinely harmful asks while not over-refusing benign ones that merely pattern-match to something risky. Push too hard and you get an annoying, over-cautious model — a visible face of the alignment tax; too soft and safety gaps open up.', 'Directly shapes the "is this model helpful or annoying" line users feel every day.', 'Fine-tune on curated refusal examples/preferences; the key metric is refusing harmful while minimizing over-refusal.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('safetyfinetuning', 'Safety fine-tuning', 'Safety Fine-Tuning', '', ARRAY['safety fine-tuning','safety finetuning','safety tuning']::text[], 'Rising', 'The fine-tuning stage that teaches a model to avoid harmful, unsafe, or policy-violating outputs.', 'A driving instructor''s final lessons — not new driving skill, but the judgment to not do dangerous things.', 'After general instruction tuning, a model gets a safety pass using refusal examples and red-team data to close known failure modes.', '[{"text":"A specific skill it instills.","id":"refusaltraining"},{"text":"The adversarial data it uses.","id":"redteamingdata"},{"text":"The cost it can impose.","id":"alignmenttax"}]'::jsonb, 'Safety fine-tuning layers guardrails onto an already-capable model using curated examples, preference data, and adversarial red-team cases. It teaches refusals, careful handling of sensitive topics, and resistance to manipulation. It is never perfect — jailbreaks keep finding gaps — and pushing it hard incurs the alignment tax, so it is a continual balancing act rather than a one-time fix.', 'The stage that makes a model shippable to the public — and the source of most "why won''t it" complaints.', 'Post-SFT tuning on safety examples, preferences, and red-team data to reduce harmful outputs.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('redteamingdata', 'Red-teaming data', 'Red-Team Data', '', ARRAY['red-teaming data','red-team data','red teaming data']::text[], 'Rising', 'Adversarial examples — crafted attempts to make a model misbehave — collected so training can patch those weaknesses.', 'Hiring ethical hackers to break into your building, then fixing every door they got through.', 'Testers spend weeks trying to jailbreak a model; the successful attacks become training data teaching it to resist next time.', '[{"text":"The stage that consumes it.","id":"safetyfinetuning"},{"text":"A related decline-behavior it reinforces.","id":"refusaltraining"}]'::jsonb, 'Red-teaming means deliberately probing a model for harmful, biased, or manipulable behavior — by humans, by other models, or both. The prompts that succeed are gold: they reveal real failure modes and become fine-tuning data so the model learns to handle them. It is an arms race, since new attacks keep appearing, which is why red-teaming is continuous rather than a single pre-launch check.', 'How known ways to break a model get found before launch — and turned into fixes.', 'Adversarially elicited failure cases used as safety fine-tuning data to close discovered vulnerabilities.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('instructiondataset', 'Instruction dataset', 'Instruction Dataset', '', ARRAY['instruction dataset','instruction data','instruction-tuning dataset']::text[], 'Core', 'A collection of task-and-response examples that teaches a base model to actually follow instructions.', 'A stack of worked "here''s the request, here''s a good reply" cards that trains a new hire on the job.', 'Thousands of pairs like "Summarize this email → a crisp summary" are assembled to fine-tune a base model into a helpful assistant.', '[{"text":"The stage that uses it.","id":"instructiontuning"},{"text":"The training method it feeds.","id":"sft"},{"text":"The format it is wrapped in.","id":"chattemplate"}]'::jsonb, 'A base model predicts text but does not naturally take orders; an instruction dataset — pairs of prompts and high-quality responses across many task types — is what teaches it to. Quality and diversity matter more than raw size; a smaller, cleaner set often beats a huge noisy one. It usually follows a chat template so the model learns roles and turns, and it is the backbone of supervised fine-tuning.', 'The raw material that turns a raw predictor into something that does what you ask.', 'Prompt/response pairs across tasks used for supervised fine-tuning; diversity and quality beat sheer volume.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('chattemplate', 'Chat template', 'Chat Template', '', ARRAY['chat template','chat formatting','conversation template']::text[], 'Core', 'The fixed format of special markers that tells a model who said what — system, user, assistant — in a conversation.', 'A screenplay''s formatting: character names and stage directions so everyone knows whose line is whose.', 'Behind a chat interface, your message gets wrapped with role markers like a user tag before the model ever sees it.', '[{"text":"The data authored in this format.","id":"instructiondataset"},{"text":"One role it marks.","id":"systemmessage"},{"text":"The unit it delimits.","id":"turn"}]'::jsonb, 'Models do not inherently know turn boundaries; a chat template encodes them with special tokens marking system, user, and assistant roles. The model is trained with this exact format, so using a mismatched template at inference degrades quality or breaks behavior. It is a small, rigid contract that carries a lot of weight — get the template wrong and even a great model acts confused.', 'An invisible formatting layer whose correctness quietly determines whether a model behaves right.', 'The role-delimiting token format a model was trained on; must match exactly at inference.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('turnbasedtraining', 'Turn-based training', 'Multi-Turn Training', '', ARRAY['turn-based training','multi-turn training','multi-turn fine-tuning']::text[], 'Rising', 'Training a model on whole back-and-forth conversations, not just single question-answer pairs, so it can hold a thread.', 'Rehearsing a full dialogue with an actor, not just isolated one-liners, so the scene actually flows.', 'The model is fine-tuned on multi-turn chats where later replies must remember and build on what was said several turns earlier.', '[{"text":"The format these transcripts use.","id":"chattemplate"},{"text":"The multi-turn structure it trains on.","id":"conversation"}]'::jsonb, 'Single-turn tuning teaches a good one-shot answer but not conversational memory or consistency. Turn-based training uses multi-turn transcripts, typically with loss computed only on the assistant''s turns, so the model learns to use prior context, stay coherent, and not contradict itself. It is what makes a model feel like it is following the conversation rather than answering each message from scratch.', 'Why a good assistant remembers what you said three messages ago instead of resetting each time.', 'Fine-tune on multi-turn transcripts with loss on assistant turns, teaching cross-turn context use and consistency.', 'Training', 60, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('rewardmodeltraining', 'Reward model training', 'Reward Model Training', '', ARRAY['reward model training','training the reward model','reward modeling']::text[], 'Core', 'Teaching a separate model to predict which responses humans prefer, so it can score outputs during RL.', 'Training a judge by showing them thousands of pairs of dishes and which one diners liked, until they can score new plates.', 'From a dataset of chosen-vs-rejected reply pairs, a model learns to output higher scores for the responses people picked.', '[{"text":"The model it produces.","id":"rewardmodel"},{"text":"The data it learns from.","id":"preferencedata"},{"text":"The pipeline it feeds.","id":"rlhf"}]'::jsonb, 'The reward model is trained on human preference comparisons to output a scalar "how good is this" score. In RLHF, that score becomes the reward signal a policy optimizes against. Its quality caps the whole pipeline: if it is exploitable, the policy will reward-hack it, and if its preferences are biased or narrow, those flaws propagate into the final model. It usually starts from the base model itself.', 'The stand-in for human judgment that scales preference feedback — and whose blind spots become the model''s.', 'Train a scalar scorer on pairwise human preferences; it provides the reward in RLHF and is a target for reward hacking.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[]),
  ('annotatoragreement', 'Annotator agreement', 'Inter-Annotator Agreement', '', ARRAY['annotator agreement','inter-annotator agreement','inter-rater reliability']::text[], 'Core', 'How often different human labelers give the same answer — a health check on whether your labels mean anything.', 'Two referees watching the same replay: if they keep disagreeing on the call, the rulebook is the problem.', 'When only 60% of annotators agree on which reply is "better," the team rewrites the guidelines before trusting the data.', '[{"text":"The activity it measures the quality of.","id":"annotation"},{"text":"A related labeling process.","id":"labeling"},{"text":"A dataset whose quality it guards.","id":"preferencedata"}]'::jsonb, 'If humans labeling the same examples do not agree, the task is ambiguous or the instructions are unclear, and a model trained on that noisy data inherits the confusion. Agreement is measured with scores like Cohen''s or Fleiss'' kappa that correct for chance. Low agreement is a signal to clarify guidelines or accept that the task has irreducible subjectivity — high agreement is a prerequisite for trustworthy labels.', 'A quick gauge of whether your labeled data is signal or noise before you build on it.', 'Chance-corrected concordance (e.g. kappa) among labelers; low values indicate ambiguous tasks or guidelines.', 'Training', 80, ARRAY['seed','training']::text[])
